    "title": "App Architecture Patterns: MVC, MVVM, MVI",
    "eli5": "Instead of dumping all your app's brains into the screen itself, you split the work into clearly separated helpers: one part holds the data, one part decides what to show, and the screen just draws whatever it is told. Patterns like MVC, MVVM, and MVI are just different, increasingly tidy recipes for how to make that split so the screen stays dumb and the logic stays testable.",
    "analogy": "Think of a TV news broadcast. The anchor (the screen) just reads the teleprompter and looks good on camera. The producer (the presentation logic) decides what goes on the teleprompter and when. The newsroom and reporters (the data/model) gather the facts. A bad show has the anchor also gathering facts and producing live on air — chaos. MVC, MVVM, and MVI are just progressively stricter rules about who is allowed to do what, so the anchor never has to also be the producer and the reporter.",
    "explanation": "As soon as a screen does more than trivial work, cramming data-fetching, business rules, and drawing all into one place makes it impossible to test, reason about, or reuse — so the whole history of UI architecture is about separating presentation logic from the UI itself. The evolution goes MVC to MVP to MVVM to MVI, and each step solves a specific pain from the one before. In classic MVC, the Model holds data, the View draws it, and the Controller handles input — but on mobile the View and Controller tend to fuse into one giant screen class (the 'massive view controller' / 'god activity'), because the framework's screen object is both. MVP answers this by introducing a Presenter that holds all presentation logic and talks to the View only through a thin interface, so the View becomes passive and testable — but the Presenter and View still hold references to each other, and keeping many methods in sync is tedious. MVVM replaces those manual calls with a ViewModel that exposes observable state; the View simply subscribes and re-renders when state changes, and crucially the ViewModel has no reference back to the View, which makes it trivially unit-testable. MVI goes one step further and enforces unidirectional data flow: the UI emits intents (user actions), those are reduced into a single immutable state object, and the UI renders that one state — no scattered mutations, one source of truth per screen. The through-line is always the same: keep presentation logic out of the UI, and reduce the number of ways state can change.\n\nAndroid vs iOS callout: On Android the canonical modern pattern is MVVM using a ViewModel that survives configuration changes and exposes observable state (LiveData / StateFlow) that the UI (Views or Jetpack Compose) collects; MVI is commonly layered on top by making that state a single immutable data class updated by a reducer. On iOS the same ideas appear as MVVM with SwiftUI, where an observable object (ObservableObject / @Observable) is the ViewModel and the View re-renders when its published properties change; unidirectional-flow frameworks like TCA (The Composable Architecture) are the MVI equivalent. Different names and observability primitives, identical goal: an observable ViewModel the UI watches, with no back-reference from logic to UI.",
    "technicalDeep": "The core mechanism that separates these patterns is how state changes propagate. In MVP it is imperative and push-based: the presenter calls view.showLoading(), view.showList(items), view.showError(msg) — one method per thing that can change, and the two objects reference each other, so both leaks and out-of-sync bugs are easy. MVVM inverts the dependency: the ViewModel merely holds observable state and the View observes it, so there is exactly one arrow of knowledge (View knows ViewModel, never the reverse), which is why the ViewModel can be tested with no UI at all — you assert on its exposed state after calling its functions. MVI tightens this into a loop: state is a single immutable value, the only way to change it is to emit an intent that a reducer turns into a new state, and the UI is a pure function of that state (render(state)). This eliminates a whole class of bugs where two code paths mutate overlapping fields, and it makes every state reproducible and loggable. The cost is boilerplate and ceremony for simple screens, so teams often use plain MVVM for simple screens and MVI where state is complex. Regardless of pattern, the presentation layer must not touch framework UI types directly if you want it testable — it works with plain data and exposes plain state.\n\nAndroid vs iOS callout: Android's ViewModel is lifecycle-scoped and deliberately holds no reference to Activities/Views or Contexts (doing so leaks them across recreation); state flows out via StateFlow/LiveData and the UI collects it lifecycle-aware. iOS's SwiftUI ViewModel is a reference type conforming to ObservableObject with @Published state (or the newer @Observable macro), and the View holds it via @StateObject; SwiftUI diffs and re-renders automatically when published state changes. Both platforms converged on the same rule — logic exposes observable state, the UI subscribes — precisely because it is what makes presentation logic unit-testable without a device or simulator.",
    "whatBreaks": "The signature failure is the 'massive view controller' or 'god activity': the screen class balloons to thousands of lines because it fetches data, applies business rules, formats strings, and draws UI all in one place, so nothing can be unit-tested and every change risks breaking something unrelated. A second break is putting business logic in the View layer of an otherwise-MVVM app (e.g. deciding in the UI whether a user is eligible for a discount), which defeats the whole point and makes the rule untestable. A third is a ViewModel that holds a reference to the View or a UI Context — on Android this leaks the Activity across configuration changes and crashes when the View is gone; it also makes the ViewModel un-unit-testable. In MVI, a common break is mutating individual fields of the state from multiple places instead of going through the single reducer, which reintroduces exactly the race-and-desync bugs MVI exists to prevent. And over-applying heavy MVI to trivial screens buries simple logic under so much ceremony that the team slows down for no benefit.",
