      "MVI makes state a single immutable value that can only change by emitting an intent that a reducer turns into a new state, and the UI is a pure function render(state). Over MVVM this buys one source of truth per screen, no partial or conflicting mutations from multiple code paths, and fully reproducible, loggable state — which is a big win when a screen has many interacting flags and async operations that can race. The cost is boilerplate: intents, a reducer, and a state class for every screen. For simple screens with a couple of fields that ceremony adds friction without preventing real bugs, so plain MVVM is the better fit there and MVI is reserved for genuinely complex state."
