    "title": "Layered & Clean Architecture",
    "eli5": "You split the app into layers like a cake: the top layer is the screens, the middle layer is your app's actual rules (what the app does), and the bottom layer is where data comes from (network, database). The key trick is that the middle rules layer knows nothing about screens or databases — it just describes what should happen. Because the rules do not depend on any framework, that knowledge works the same no matter what tools you use.",
    "analogy": "Think of a restaurant. The dining room (presentation) is where customers are served. The recipes and the head chef's rules (domain) decide what a dish is and how it should turn out. The suppliers and pantry (data) provide ingredients. A great kitchen writes its recipes so they do not depend on which specific supplier delivered the tomatoes — swap suppliers freely, the recipe is unchanged. The recipe (your business rules) points at abstract 'ingredients', not at 'Bob's Tomato Company'. That inward-pointing independence is the whole idea.",
    "explanation": "Layered (and its stricter cousin Clean) architecture organizes an app into three concentric layers — presentation, domain, and data — with one non-negotiable rule about which way dependencies are allowed to point. The presentation layer is the UI and its ViewModels/presenters: it shows state and forwards user actions. The domain layer is the heart: it holds the business rules and use-cases (also called interactors) — the pure 'what the app does' expressed with no reference to any UI framework, database, or network library. The data layer implements how data is actually fetched and stored: network clients, databases, caches, exposed to the rest of the app through repository interfaces. The dependency rule is the crux: dependencies point inward, toward the domain. Presentation depends on domain; data depends on domain; but the domain depends on nothing outward — it does not import Android, iOS, Retrofit, Room, URLSession, or any concrete detail. This is achieved by defining the interfaces (repository contracts) in the domain and implementing them in the data layer, so the arrow of dependency is inverted at that boundary. The payoff is exactly what makes this course framework-agnostic: because your business rules never touch a framework, that knowledge and often that code transfers unchanged to any framework or platform, and it can be tested in plain, fast unit tests with everything outward mocked.\n\nAndroid vs iOS callout: Google's official architecture guidance is literally these three layers — a UI layer (ViewModel + UI state), an optional domain layer of use-cases, and a data layer of repositories and data sources — with repository interfaces mediating so the UI never talks to Retrofit/Room directly. On iOS the same structure is idiomatic Swift: SwiftUI/UIKit views and view models in presentation, plain Swift structs and protocol-based use-cases in the domain, and repository implementations wrapping URLSession/CoreData in the data layer. Both ecosystems land on identical layering because the dependency rule is a language-agnostic principle, not a platform feature.",
    "technicalDeep": "The mechanism that enforces 'domain depends on nothing outward' is the Dependency Inversion Principle: the domain declares an interface it needs (e.g. UserRepository with getUser()), and the data layer provides a concrete class that implements it (UserRepositoryImpl talking to network + cache). At compile time the domain module has zero dependency on the data module; instead the data module depends on the domain to implement its interface, and something at the outer edge (composition root / DI graph) wires the concrete implementation in at runtime. Use-cases (interactors) are small single-purpose objects in the domain that orchestrate business rules — GetFeed, PlaceOrder, ApplyDiscount — each callable and testable in isolation, keeping ViewModels thin and preventing rules from leaking into the UI. A crucial discipline is that data crossing layers is often mapped: the data layer's DTOs (shaped by the API/DB) are converted to domain models (shaped by business meaning), so a change in the API's JSON shape does not ripple into your business rules. The cost of all this is indirection and boilerplate — interfaces, mappers, extra classes — so pragmatic teams collapse the domain layer for trivial CRUD screens and add it back where real business logic lives. But the invariant they never break is the direction of dependency: nothing inner may import anything outer.\n\nAndroid vs iOS callout: On Android this is often physically enforced with Gradle modules — a pure-Kotlin domain module with no Android dependencies at all (it will not even compile against the Android SDK), and app/data modules depending on it — so a violation is a build error, not a code-review nicety. On iOS the same boundary is enforced with separate Swift packages / targets (e.g. a Domain package that imports no UIKit/SwiftUI), with protocols in Domain and implementations in a Data package. Both use the module/package boundary as a compiler-enforced wall so the dependency rule cannot be violated by accident.",
    "whatBreaks": "The defining break is a leaky domain: business logic imports framework types — a use-case that references an Android Context, a domain model annotated with database or JSON serialization attributes, or a repository interface that returns a Retrofit Response — which chains your rules to a framework and destroys both testability and portability. A related break is the UI reaching straight into the data layer (a ViewModel calling the HTTP client directly), skipping the domain and scattering business rules into screens. Another is skipping DTO-to-domain mapping so the API's exact JSON shape becomes your app's internal model — then any backend change forces edits across every layer. Over-engineering is the opposite failure: adding use-cases, interfaces, and mappers for a trivial screen that just displays a value, burying simple code under ceremony. And getting the dependency direction backwards — having the domain depend on the data layer instead of inverting through an interface — technically 'works' but removes the entire benefit, because now the core cannot be tested or reused without dragging the framework along.",
