    "seniorNotes": "The one invariant senior engineers guard above all is the dependency rule: nothing inner may depend on anything outer, and the domain must be a pure island with zero framework imports — that single property is what makes business knowledge portable across Flutter, React Native, Kotlin, and Swift and testable in milliseconds. They enforce it structurally, not by good intentions: a domain module/package that literally cannot compile against the UI framework turns a violation into a build failure. They also stay pragmatic about the layer count — a full domain layer with use-cases where there is real business logic, a collapsed two-layer shape for CRUD screens — because ceremony without logic is just cost. And they insist on mapping at boundaries (DTO to domain model) so the shape of an external API or database never dictates the shape of the core. The tell they look for: if reusing your business rules requires dragging along Retrofit or UIKit, the layering has failed regardless of how many folders exist.",
